node.text:
A journey of extreme lava flows from the ongoing eruption in Geldingadalur on Iceland's Reykjanes peninsula. 

A huge thanks to @france.fabris for the incredible live field recordings from the eruption site, and to @ethermachines, a fellow Australian in Iceland, for the beautiful tracks he composed for the Netflix series Dark. 

Finally, thank you to @eydismariaolafs for the camera assistance and operating the B-cam.

Shot on RED Dragon-6K and DJI Inspire II.

#iceland #volcano #lava

Before wrapping up the virtual exhibition for Echoes of the North, I wanted to sit down with you guys and share some more of the backstory and vision behind my new print series. Hope you have enjoyed seeing the images this week and I really appreciate all of your positive feedback and support on the print collection so far, thank you guys 🙌🏼

There’s just 5 hours left on the sale if you are looking to pick up a print! Link in bio.

node.text:
An autumn trip through the south of Iceland with the @djiglobal RS2. 

Lately I’ve been really fascinated by the potential of adding motion to my images. Finding small elements in the landscape that can tell a deeper story through movement rather than a still image. 

I’ve been really stoked with the RS2, it can fit in my hiking bag, has really strong motors to keep all my different setups stable and has enabled me to begin this new chapter. Excited to share more of my videos with you guys, it’s just the beginning 🤘🏼
#DJIRS2

A visual journey through the biggest fjord system on earth, Scoresbysund in East Greenland.

Thank you to @northsailing for making this trip possible in their beautiful wooden schooner named Hildur. Music by @olafurarnalds.

node.text:
The transition to cinema. 
It’s been over a year since I jumped into the world of natural history filmmaking. I can’t say I’ve ever been more busy in my life, but today I had a realisation that I’ve been forgetting the backbone my whole profession. The still image has a special power to encapsulate a huge amount of emotion and story telling in one frame. In the now endless pursuit of sequence building for cinematic filmmaking, I’ve definitely overlooked this power. 

I’m excited to dedicate some time this summer to capture still photographs, and dive into the art that has given me so much joy over the years. This image always comes to mind for that very reason - I captured it with my first ever camera.

Hope you are all well ✌🏼

node.text:
The times has finally come. Join me in Antarctica 🇦🇶
I’m excited to announce my next photography workshop and sailing adventure expedition. You’ll have the opportunity to join me as we set sail for Antarctica on the beautiful tall ship @barkeuropa for a one of a kind expedition.

It’s been a dream to visit Antarctica for many years. I’ve sailed all over the Arctic, but never yet managed to venture to the other end of the world, so you’ll join me on a very special first trip. 

We’ll be living the adventurous @barkeuropa sailing lifestyle for 22 days, authentically experiencing the drake passage by sail and the unique wonders of the Antarctic peninsula along the way. 

I’ll be the hosting photography lectures for everyone on board and will be there to guide you through shooting and processing images of the beautiful polar landscape. 

The expedition dates are December 9th to 30th 2021. This means we’ll spend the festive season together on board at the southern tip of the globe - what a treat that will be! 

Head to the link in my bio to learn more about the expedition.

Special thanks to Richard Simko and Jordi Plana Morales for the images of the ship!

The colder side of Iceland with the #DJIAir2S from @djiglobal. 

I took a break from the lava to head east and see how the spring is developing around the glaciers. The 12km long range transmission and 4 direction obstacle sensing on the DJI Air 2S allowed me to get right into the heart of the action, flying far out over the ice edge.

Never a dull moment here in Iceland, I feel so grateful to be able to call this country home 🇮🇸

node.text:
A trip over the lava with @benjaminhardman and the new #DJIAir2S from @djiglobal.

The eruption is changing at an incredible rate these days, with new craters constantly appearing around the valley. Capturing high resolution cinematic footage has been made easy with this new lightweight and compact drone, especially when needing to hike in to the eruption site. With such vast transformation occurring every day, it’s addictive to be out there. I like to call it volcano fever 🌋 
#iceland #volcano #eruption

node.text: Exploring the eruption with the @djiglobal Air 2S. It’s been a month since the lava started to flow, and I’ve been putting the #DJIAir2S to the test ever since. I’ve been blown away by the level of detail that this tiny compact drone can capture. With a 1-inch sensor for stills and 5.4k 10-bit video resolution, it really is the all in one machine for a lightweight run and gun setup. Stay tuned for more 🤘🏼

Music: @ethermachines

Enjoy the eruption! 🌋

node.text:
A journey of extreme lava flows from the ongoing eruption in Geldingadalur on Iceland's Reykjanes peninsula. 

A huge thanks to @france.fabris for the incredible live field recordings from the eruption site, and to @ethermachines, a fellow Australian in Iceland, for the beautiful tracks he composed for the Netflix series Dark. 

Finally, thank you to @eydismariaolafs for the camera assistance and operating the B-cam.

Shot on RED Dragon-6K and DJI Inspire II.

node.text:
Iceland Erupts through the eyes of @benjaminhardman.
As the skies opened up this morning, we witnessed the first views of the new eruption on the Reykjanes peninsula, right outside of the capital region. It’s the first time that lava has reached the surface here in over 800 years. 

I’ve been waiting for a very long time to connect with this side of Iceland, moving my life here just after the last eruption. Today was an incredibly impactful day, to see nature in its most raw form, creating new earth as its done for millions of years before us. 
Thank you for a life changing experience nature. 

Follow me @benjaminhardman for more insights into the eruption very soon.
